<\/p>\n\n<p>D = X11 * (X11 + X12 + X21 + X22 - X11) - X11X21 - X11X12 - X12X21<\/p>\n\n<p>D = X11 * (X12 + X21 + X22) - X11X21 - X11X12 - X12X21<\/p>\n\n<p>D = X11X12 + X11X21 + X11X22 - X11X21 - X11X12 - X12X21<\/p>\n\n<p>D = X11X22 - X12X21<\/p>\n\n<p>Sorry for the very long answer, but I thought it would be more clear if I wrote everything out.<\/p>\n","answer_id":16839,"question_id":16835,"up_vote_count":5}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16835/definition-of-linkage-desiquilibrium-ld","last_activity_date":1408893927,"creation_date":1398355057,"answer_count":1,"title":"Definition of Linkage Desiquilibrium (LD)","body":"<p>According to <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linkage_disequilibrium\" rel=\"nofollow\">wiki<\/a>, linkage disequilibrium $D$ equals<\/p>\n\n<p>$$D = x_{11} - p_1\\cdot q_1$$<\/p>\n\n<p>where:<\/p>\n\n<p>$$\n        \\begin{matrix}\n        \\text{Haplotype} &amp; \\text{Frequency}\\\\\n        A_1B_1 &amp; x_{11}\\\\\n        A_{1}B_{2} &amp; x_{12} \\\\\n        A_{2}B_{1} &amp; x_{21} \\\\\n        A_{2}B_{2} &amp; x_{22} \\\\\n        \\end{matrix}\n$$<\/p>\n\n<p>and<\/p>\n\n<p>$$\n        \\begin{matrix}\n        \\text{Allele} &amp; \\text{Frequency}\\\\\n    A_{1} &amp; p_{1}=x_{11}+x_{12} \\\\\n    A_{2} &amp; p_{2}=x_{21}+x_{22} \\\\\n    B_{1} &amp; q_{1}=x_{11}+x_{21} \\\\\n    B_{2} &amp; q_{2}=x_{12}+x_{22} \\\\\n        \\end{matrix}\n$$<\/p>\n\n<p>According to <a href=\"http://books.google.ca/books/about/Principles_of_Population_Genetics.html?id=4ypuQgAACAAJ&amp;redir_esc=y\" rel=\"nofollow\">Hartl and Clark<\/a>, linkage disequilibrium $D$ equals:<\/p>\n\n<p>$$D = x_{11}x_{22}-x_{12}x_{21}$$ <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Question<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Can you please prove that these two formulations of linkage disequilibrium are equivalent (assuming that they are equivalent)? If they're not\u2026 Do we use different definitions? What are their respective meanings?<\/p>\n","question_id":16835,"tags":["evolution","na