ds are an accepted method in nutrition research.<\/p>\n\n<p>My 2-year-old child exhibited the symptoms described above, after consuming two Oreo biscuits in the afternoon. That evenings soiled nappy (diaper) revealed a dark but otherwise well-textured stool. When my concerned partner brought this to my attention, it immediately reminded me of the use of carmine red and related food dyes for the measurement of gastrointestinal transit times. The principle here is that the dyes are not absorbed in the gut, so the time from consumption to excretion gives a measure of bowel function. Short transit time means no constipation and is considered a sign of great bowel function.<\/p>\n\n<p>Based on the observations reported for Oreos, my educated guess would be that Oreo products contain miniscule amounts of non-absorbed colorants - something that is generally regarded as safe. Self-reported symptoms are generally considered valid by health professionals. I am still intrigued by the Oreo colouring puzzle, as this colourant must be natural.  <\/p>\n","answer_id":13710,"question_id":9487,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1395772967}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9487/why-is-my-faeces-black-in-color-after-eating-oreos","last_activity_date":1408859129,"creation_date":1375069813,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why is my faeces black in color after eating Oreos","body":"<p>Why is my faeces black in colour the morning after I eat some <strong>Oreos<\/strong>?<br>\n<strong>Day 1<\/strong> : Eat a handful of Oreos &amp; the next morning your stool is black.<br>\n<strong>Day 3<\/strong> : Eat a handful of cocoa flavored biscuits &amp; the next morning your stool is normal.<br>\n<strong>Day 5<\/strong> : Eat a handful of Chocolates &amp; the next morning your stool is normal.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have experienced similar thing where stool has a reddish tint after consuming excessive beet root. But it just takes a \nhandful of Oreos to turn it black. But with any other biscuits or chocolates, my faeces is a normal \nyellowish.  <\/p>\n\n<p>I don't have anything other than anecdotal evidence but a lot (<strong>NOT ALL<\/strong>) of my friends have had similar experience. Just Googling \"<strong><a href=\"http://www.google.com/search?q=Black+stool+after+eating+Oreos\" rel=\"nofollow\">Black stool after eating Oreos<\/a><\/strong>\" &amp; I see a lot of people (not all) having similar experience.   <\/p>\n\n<p>Why is that the case? Why doesn't it happen to everybody?\nWhat ingredient in Oreos makes it happen? Why it happens \nwith reference to metabolism of our body? It doesn't affect my body in any way, although I can't \nbe sure. \nAsking this question with curiosity than caution. Looking for medical/biological/biochemical perspective.<\/p>\n","question_id":9487,"tags":["metabolism"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":13710,"down_vote_count":2,"is_answered":true,"view_count":18518,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1375087506},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd1d0a047c420a11e70447579204292f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8919,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8919/happyjennifer","reputation":11,"display_name":"HappyJennifer"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/20736/subtypes-of-acute-myeloid-leukemia","last_activity_date":1408855282,"creation_date":1408848964,"answer_count":0,"title":"Subtypes of Acute myeloid leukemia","body":"<p>I am a computer scientist with no biological background and working on analyzing lab  results of patients with Acute myeloid leukemia. They have been tagged with following subtypes of AML:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>AML with No maturation<\/li>\n<li>AML with granulocytic differentiation<\/li>\n<li>AML with monocytic  differentitaion.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>I know there are two classifications for AML subtypes: FAB(M0-M7) and WHO. I think these patients have been classified using FAB, but their corresponding subtypes' names do not match in any of the names associated with M0-M7:  <a href=\"http://www.cancer.org/cancer/leukemia-acutemyeloidaml/detailedguide/leukemia-acute-myeloid-myelogenous-classified\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.cancer.org/cancer/leukemia-acutemyeloidaml/detailedguide/leukemia-acute-myeloid-myelogenous-classified<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>I checked a lot of literature but still not sure about the class of the last two tags in FAB classification. Could someone please help me with that?<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>\"AML with No maturation\"  is M1?<\/li>\n<li>\"AML with granulocytic differentiation\" is M2 (or M4, M5) ?<\/li>\n<li>\"AML with monocytic  differentiation\" is M4 or M5 or both ?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":20736,"tags":["immunology","pathology","cancer"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":35,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1408855282},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2a0694d7574295307f53e371931cf60c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8856,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8856/user1301593","reputation":21,"display_name":"user1301593"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/de2c4fd753821f85c74d886aa17410de?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":107,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/107/kmm","reputation":8486,"display_name":"kmm"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1408833993,"creation_date":1408833993,"body":"<p>The methods should be equivalent, given the same data. Using <code>phylosignal<\/code>'s demo:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>library(\"picante\")\nlibrary(\"phytools\")\n\nset.seed(5)\nrandtree &lt;- rcoal(20)\nrandtraits &lt;- rTraitCont(randtree)\n\nphylosignal(randtraits[randtree$tip.label],randtree)\n\nphylosig(randtree, randtraits[randtree$tip.label], method=\"K\",test=TRUE)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><code>phylosignal<\/code> returns:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>         K PIC.variance.obs PIC.variance.rnd.mean PIC.variance.P PIC.variance.Z\n1 1.430635          0.01147             0.4631411          0.001      -2.662701\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and <code>phylosig<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>$K\n[1] 1.430635\n\n$P\n[1] 0.001\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Both give K = 1.430635 and an identical P-value. <\/p>\n\n<p>Mathematically, it shouldn't matter if you shuffle the trait values or generate a null distribution of K. To get a null distribution for K, you have to shuffle something, and the tip values are probably being shuffled. You could check the code to be sure. An analogy is that, when doing a randomization for an ANOVA-like test, you can either shuffle the observed values or the group membership. Either way will give the same answer.<\/p>\n\n<p>As for interpretation, Brownian motion is the simplest model for trait evolution, implying no direction, optima, rate changes, etc. K = 1 when the observed variation equals the expected variation. If K is greater than 1 then neighboring tips tend to resemble each other more than you would expect, suggesting a deviation from Brownian motion. <\/p>\n","answer_id":20735,"question_id":20668,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/20668/null-distribution-of-blombergs-k","last_activity_date":1408833993,"creation_date":1408648807,"answer_count":1,"title":"Null distribution of Blomberg's K","body":"<p>I've noticed different functions in different R libraries have different ways of assessing significance for Blomberg's K. For instance, picante's phylosignal looks at a distribution of PIC variance values from shuffled trait values to assess significance; when phytool's phylosig calculates a null distribution of Blomberg K values for shuffled traits.<\/p>\n\n<p>What is the interpretative difference between the two and when should one approach be used over another? And what does it mean if the observed Blomberg's K is greater than 1 (traits less similar than expected under Brownian Motion model of evolution), but significantly greater (or less) than the null distribution of Blomberg's K-values?<\/p>\n","question_id":20668,"tags":["ecology","phylogenetics","community-ecology"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":519,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f44b47d4d5e48ed503d3f7f53194b1ed?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":975,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/975/trig","reputation":232,"display_name":"TRiG"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1b3c5b025ca581db5a8fdd2564b5367c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6511,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6511/bez","reputation":2430,"display_name":"Bez"},"score":0,"post_id":20731,"edited":false,"creation_date":1408828933,"comment_id":32350,"body":"I assume because if a disease is contracted and mutated at a certain rate, then the chances of it developing further into new strains in a large number of population is faster than lets say the few native colonies, hence if you stretch this through time you can see that even the simplest of viruses that people have build immunity to over say 100 years can be deadly to a few that might have never encountered the virus before. but thats just my guess."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user1357"},"score":0,"post_id":20731,"edited":false,"creation_date":1408858622,"comment_id":32359,"body":"<a href=\"http://history.stackexchange.com/questions/15036/did-syphilis-polio-hepatitis-and-encephalitis-come-to-general-world-from-the\" title=\"did syphilis polio hepatitis and encephalitis come to general world from the\">history.stackexchange.com/questions/15036/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c035c3dad7340b6ecd52be8b344c4b4a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4617,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4617/ben-crowell","reputation":136,"dis