ng>humidity is high as well as warm temperature<\/strong>.<\/p>\n\n<p>For laying eggs she will dig a tunnel inside and close the gates. She won't eat or move and <strong>completely avoid light<\/strong>, if the eggs are unhatched or some other problem occurs <strong>she will eats her own eggs<\/strong>. After around 8-10 weeks eggs will pop and you will get new worker ant babies. They will form the hive and feed the queen ant.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://www.alexanderwild.com/Ants/Natural-History/Metamorphosis-Ant-Brood/i-v4sN9kk/2/XL/gracilis2-XL.jpg\" alt=\"\">    <\/p>\n\n<p>More info: <a href=\"http://antnest.co.uk/colony.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://antnest.co.uk/colony.html<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":19808,"question_id":19807,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/19807/why-does-ant-queen-keep-the-eggs-out-of-her-hive","last_activity_date":1408716267,"creation_date":1405876445,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why does ant queen keep the eggs out of her hive?","body":"<p><a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/q/19582/6918\">I have captured an ant queen<\/a> and now I'm trying to create an artificial ant nest.  <\/p>\n\n<p>I have noticed that though she has dug a hole to hide in, she keeps the eggs out of it unless she feels that they are in danger.<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/tmS03.jpg\" alt=\"ant queen reaching for her eggs\"><\/p>\n\n<p>I have two theories explaining why she does that:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Ants naturally put eggs in sunlight to keep them warm. In her situation, they are not gonna be any warmer of course - the jar is whole about the same temperature.<\/li>\n<li>She is digging a nest and she needs some space. If this is true, where is all the dirt?<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","question_id":19807,"tags":["ethology","ant"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":266,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1406122048},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/B7pRr.jpg?s=128&g=1","user