w.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":20654,"edited":false,"creation_date":1410182505,"comment_id":33126,"body":"Nope, this is the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paratope\" rel=\"nofollow\">paratope<\/a>. The epitope is the part of the antigen which is recognized by the antibody."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1408621360,"creation_date":1408613407,"body":"<p>Lets define the nomenclature first: An <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antigen\">antigen<\/a> is a large structure (protein, virus, bacteria and so an) which is recognized by the immune system as foreign. The word antigen derives from the abbreviation ANTIbody GENerator. Exposure of our immune system to an antigen results in an immune response and the generation of many antibodies.<\/p>\n\n<p>An <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epitope\">epitope<\/a> is a small part of an antigen - typically these are small structural elements or small peptides (8-11 amino acids in length) which are recognized by the binding site of an antibody. See the picture below (from <a href=\"http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epitop\">here<\/a>):<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/4J23O.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Here the antigen is the albumin protein. On the surface you can see 8 different epitopes which lead to the generation of 8 highly specific antibodies against the epitopes (antikörper is the german word for antibody). Every antibodies is highly specific for its epitope and will recognize no other epitope and helps raising an immune response against it. What happens after an antibody bound to its epitope can be read <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antibody#Function\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Antibodies directed against a protective epitope are directed against (highly) conserved structures of the antigen. For example the recognize a highly conserved structure of a virus which means that even when this virus mutates (like influenza does) it will still recognize the conserved epitope and give protection against this virus (or better: antigen).<\/p>\n","answer_id":20654,"question_id":20652,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1408621360}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/20652/what-is-a-protective-epitope","last_activity_date":1408667236,"creation_date":1408599235,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is a protective epitope?","body":"<p>What is a protective epitope? An epitope is basically a part of antigen. So does it mean that when the epitope combines with an antibody, it helps in the functioning of the antibody instead of going against it?<\/p>\n","question_id":20652,"tags":["molecular-biology","immunology","antibody"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":20654,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":413,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1408667236},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e86681e49622d52817b36fd2a4c936b7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":8014,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8014/martin-thoma","reputation":441,"display_name":"Martin Thoma","accept_rate":83},"closed_date":1408745417,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/KD6Fx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3952,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3952/oreotrephes","reputation":4267,"display_name":"Oreotrephes","accept_rate":86},"score":1,"post_id":20675,"edited":false,"creation_date":1408669178,"comment_id":32203,"body":"cf <a href=\"http://gardening.stackexchange.com/questions/2609/what-is-this-fast-growing-plant-with-blue-black-berries/2610#2610\" title=\"what is this fast growing plant with blue black berries\">gardening.stackexchange.com/questions/2609/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.co