919,"edited":false,"creation_date":1342611544,"comment_id":4253,"body":"I think you may need to specify to what degree of damage... increased muscle strength is (in part) achieved by damage to the old tissue, which is then repaired by immune and stem cells. At least, that&#39;s how skeletal muscle works. This differs massively from the kind of damage that impairs the function of that muscle/bone/whatever (e.g. a break/fracture). You can rest and recover from a broken bone. You die from a &#39;broken&#39; heart (excuse the expression). I will be very interested to see an in depth answer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"score":0,"post_id":2919,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9bbe3bd8b81991d8ccf5c6763edb1184?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":740,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/740/luke","reputation":4547,"display_name":"Luke","accept_rate":69},"edited":false,"creation_date":1342612103,"comment_id":4254,"body":"Erm. I don&#39;t have an answer )+: just lots of inane questions"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"score":1,"post_id":2919,"edited":false,"creation_date":1342623837,"comment_id":4257,"body":"Heart muscles aren&#39;t the only exception: think of neurons. Once they&#39;re dead, they&#39;re gone for good."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexc