ry small drop of blood."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":20523,"edited":false,"creation_date":1408118840,"comment_id":30873,"body":"In fact a lot of tests are not done using a microscope. And besides that, you can not see molecules in the microscope. You can see cells. Typical amounts for blood tests are 4.5 or 9 ml which is not very much. Enough to handle and prepare the sample and to repeat it, if something goes wrong."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/wMxBb.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6035,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6035/user6035","reputation":175,"display_name":"user6035","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":20523,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1408119366,"comment_id":30875,"body":"@Chris So is it a question of technology/affordability? Are we capable of obtaining the information from a very small drop of blood?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":20523,"edited":false,"creation_date":1408120587,"comment_id":30876,"body":"That depends on the type of test you want to do."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/wMxBb.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6035,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6035/user6035","repu