comment_id":5911,"body":"@terdon not arguing, it is just important to correct so the information will be clear. Consider a PWM that in first position has A with probability 1 and second position C with probability 1. The sequence AA has a probability of zero for binding this sequence (1*0), but the sum will give you 1, which is half the maximal score and thus clearly wrong. PWM is a probabilistic model of the binding affinity so it has to be manipulated as probabilities."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1408129655,"creation_date":1349987747,"body":"<p>According to [this page][1], you should take the sum and not the product:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Once a Profile has been derived from a set of functionally related\n  sites, the Profile can be used to scan a query sequence for the\n  presence of potential sites. Usually you run a window the length of\n  the matrix along the sequence, and sum the coefficients from the\n  matrix corresponding to each nucleotide in each position on the window\n  sequence. Formally, the score of a matrix M for a site s of length l\n  (s = s1, ... , sl, and sk being one of {A, C, G, T}) is computed as<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>$m_s=\\sum\\limits_{j=1}^lM_{s_{lj}}$<\/p>\n\n<p>I highly recommend you read the rest of the page, the author, Roderic Guigó, is an authority on the subject. <\/p>\n","answer_id":3904,"question_id":3901,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1408129655},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a43651dba3f306d9c0c0b92a7457722?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1441,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1441/bitwise","reputation":1705,"display_name":"Bitwise"},"score":9,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0432f2c6c91d86fdf110ab0b8d3b5bbb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1526,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1526/omar","reputation":141,"display_name":"Omar"},"score":0,"post_id":3906,"edited":false,"creation_date":1350018227,"comment_id":5906,"body":"Thank you for that detailed answer! I am trying to get scored between 0 and 1 (i.e. a probability).  I thought about taking the ratio of the score to the best match to the PWM. I&#39;m guessing from what you just explained, I would have to divide by 0.004 for the sequence score and the best score. So using the score from BAAC : (0.072/0.004)/(0.18/0.004)? Would this work?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0432f2c6c91d86fdf110ab0b8d3b5bbb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1526,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1526/omar","reputation":141,"display_name":"Omar"},"score":0,"post_id":3906,"edited":false,"creation_date":1350019826,"comment_id":5907,"body":"Also, if I have real life background probabilities (i.e. determined from a large database) would I just take the product of everything?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a43651dba3f306d9c0c0b92a7457722?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1441,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1441/bitwise","reputation":1705,"display_name":"Bitwise"},"score":0,"post_id":3906,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0432f2c6c91d86fdf110ab0b8d3b5bbb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1526,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1526/omar","reputation":141,"display_name":"Omar"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1350049428,"comment_id":5912,"body":"@Omar regarding normalizing the score between 0 and 1, you can normalize the score in the way you suggested (note that the background model probability cancels out so you don&#39;t need it). The interpretation then will be different, as it will not tell you anything about how likely it is to find your sequence by random. So I guess it depends what you want to use the scores for. Note that as long as you divide all your sequences by a constant score, be it background or the highest probability, the ratios between the scores of different sequences will be maintained."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6a43651dba3f306d9c0c0b92a7457722?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1441,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1441/bitwise","reputation":1705,"display_name":"Bitwise"},"score":0,"post_id":3906,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0432f2c6c91d86fdf110ab0b8d3b5bbb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1526,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1526/omar","reputation":141,"display_name":"Omar"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1350049577,"comment_id":5913,"body":"@Omar regarding background models, if you are not using uniform background and you are making predictions on a given organism, it would make sense to calculate the A/C/G/T percent of the whole genome, and use that as the background model, i.e. PWM with the same length as your PWM of interest, just that all positions have the same genomic probabilities."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0432f2c6c91d86fdf110ab0b8d3b5bbb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1526,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1526/omar","reputation":141,"display_name":"Omar"},"score":0,"post_id":3906,"edited":false,"creation_date":1350059588,"comment_id":5914,"body":"Thanks. I am using amino acid sequences so I guess the background model would be (1/20)^15 then. I run into the problem when dividing the product of my score by the product of the best score since they are both very small numbers: for example 10^-19 / 10^-12 = 10^-7, which is indeed between 0 and 1 but it does not give me a sense of how similar it is to the best. What I am looking to score is how well some peptide matches a PWM (ranging from 0 to 1). Does this make sense? Appreciate the help"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.grava