ttled water will differ in their mineral content as well (<a href=\"http://www.google.co.in/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=7&amp;ved=0CEwQFjAG&amp;url=http://www.nuffieldfoundation.org/sites/default/files/files/FSMQ%2520Mineral%2520water%281%29.doc&amp;ei=-AmOU5vpKpe78gX_x4LoBA&amp;usg=AFQjCNGl0GTfR-rGSFwda4tZ_v3pkDWhyg&amp;sig2=T1Yzth_8SbrIWebz9gMS5Q&amp;bvm=bv.68191837,d.dGc\">reference<\/a>). The place where you stay might be lacking in a particular mineral that your body requires which is why your doctor has specified the use of a particular brand of mineral water. <\/p>\n","answer_id":17868,"question_id":17867,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b771a341bd46dde26aac28aae1881ee9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4025,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4025/jan","reputation":459,"display_name":"Jan"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1408030498,"creation_date":1408030498,"body":"<p>The main minerals in tap water are calcium and magnesium, which determine the hardness of water. The main minerals in mineral waters are calcium, magnesium, sodium, chloride, carbonate and sulfate. Tap water from different regions and various brands of mineral water can contain very different amounts of minerals, so it is impossible to make a general recommendation to drink more mineral water.<\/p>\n\n<p>Mineral water high in calcium or magnesium can be a good source of calcium and magnesium for people who do not get enough calcium from foods. Foods are much better source of calcium and magnesium than water, though. <\/p>\n\n<p>Researchers from the World Health Organization (WHO) claim that water hardness (calcium and magnesium content) has no effects on health (positive or negative).<\/p>\n\n<p>Foods high in calcium, beneficial and harmful effects of calcium and references to claims I made:\n<a href=\"http://www.nutrientsreview.com/minerals/calcium-ca.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.nutrientsreview.com/minerals/calcium-ca.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Calcium concentration in bottled and mineral waters (US, Europe):\n<a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2488164/table/Tab2/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2488164/table/Tab2/<\/a> <\/p>\n","answer_id":20497,"question_id":17867,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17867/tap-vs-mineral-water-for-drinking","last_activity_date":1408030498,"creation_date":1401815319,"answer_count":2,"title":"Tap vs. mineral water for drinking","body":"<p>I was told a human should drink a small glass (0,3 liter) of mineral water per day to get the minerals. What is the rationale behind this? What is the difference between tap water and mineral water in terms of nutrition facts and effects on human health?<\/p>\n\n<p>Values for tap water in my area: <\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://snag.gy/5A9MV.jpg\" alt=\"\"> <\/p>\n\n<p>How good are the values regarding nutrition facts?<\/p>\n","question_id":17867,"tags":["human-biology","nutrition"],"score":6,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":224,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1401918901},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/66a4a4ef4bf3fea69a5964e872991e21?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6363,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6363/wajih-aziza","reputation":45,"display_name":"Wajih Aziza"},"closed_date":1408005967,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":0,"post_id":20476,"edited":false,"creation_date":1407994380,"comment_id":30771,"body":"Can you expand your question? At the moment I am not really sure in which direction you are thinking."},{"owner":{"