the receptor, which is not conserved in its homologues.<\/p>\n\n<p>In terms of solutions as pointed in the comments, the best way to go about this is to use a polyclonal Ab, which is raised against a large section of the peptide in question, allowing you a better chance of its detection. If that did not work, you might have to resort to GLP-1 mRNA detection using RT-PCR or qPCR, which you would need to design primers for based on you GPL-1 sequence which you can get help with <a href=\"http://openwetware.org/wiki/Choosing_primers_for_qPCR\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":20485,"question_id":15012,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1408007600}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/15012/how-do-you-express-and-detect-glp-1-receptors","last_activity_date":1408007600,"creation_date":1392300859,"answer_count":1,"title":"How do you express and detect GLP-1 receptors?","body":"<p>I am currently working with a peptide which is an analogue for glp-1, but during invitro studies am not able to detect for the presence of GLP1- receptors.\nThe cell line used is Min-6. How do I detect it? <\/p>\n","question_id":15012,"tags":["biochemistry","molecular-biology","endocrinology","biotechnology","diabetes-mellitus"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":63,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/39b7eb876a5036084ea54aecc1b888b1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3338/rrs-ghost","reputation":170,"display_name":"RRs_Ghost","accept_rate":40},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avat